'''Myōhō Hakase''' (明法博士, みょうほうはかせ) was an [[official]] belonging to the {{ill|Daigakuryō|ja|大学寮|12=draft}} under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft}} in ancient Japan. It was an {{ill|Extraordinary Office|ja|令外官|12=draft}} with two positions. Initially, it was ranked as ''Shōshichii-ge'' (正七位下). Later, it came to be filled by members of prestigious families.
== History == Myōhō Hakase was established along with {{ill|Monjō Hakase|ja|文章博士|12=draft}} under the {{ill|Kaku|ja|格式|12=draft}} issued on {{ill|July 21 (lunar calendar)|ja|7月21日 (旧暦)|12=draft}} of {{ill|Shinki|ja|神亀|12=draft}} 5 (August 30, 728)<ref> {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft}}, entry for Daibō (8th day) of the 8th month of Taika Gannen. This record mentions dispatching Myōhō Hakase to various circuits (excluding Saikaidō) to explain the {{ill|Taihō Ritsuryō|ja|大宝律令|12=draft}}. There are theories that Myōhō Hakase existed during the {{ill|Asuka Kiyomihara Ritsuryō|ja|飛鳥浄御原令|12=draft}} period but was not established under the Taihō Ritsuryō, and that the term referred to 'officials knowledgeable in laws.' (Yukio Hisaki, ''Study of Ancient Japanese Schools'' (1990, Tamagawa University Press) ISBN 4-4720-7981-X).</ref>.
Initially, it was called '''Ritsugaku Hakase''' (律学博士), but after the establishment of {{ill|Meihōsei|ja|明法生|12=draft}} on {{ill|March 27 (lunar calendar)|ja|3月27日 (旧暦)|12=draft}} of {{ill|Tenpyō|ja|天平|12=draft}} 2 (April 18, 730), it was soon renamed '''Myōhō Hakase'''. Under Myōhō Hakase were '''Myōhō Tokugyōshō''' (明法得業生) with 2 positions and '''Myōhōshō''' (明法生) with 10 positions (later increased to 20). Over time, one of the key duties was drafting and submitting {{ill|Meihō Kanbun|ja|明法勘文|12=draft}}, legal opinions during court discussions like {{ill|Jinden|ja|陣定|12=draft}}.
By the mid-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|12=draft}}, the positions became hereditary among the {{ill|Sanuki clan|ja|讃岐氏|12=draft}} and {{ill|Imomune clan|ja|惟宗氏|12=draft}}, but during the medieval period, these were replaced by the renowned {{ill|Sakanoue clan|ja|坂上氏|12=draft}} and {{ill|Nakahara clan|ja|中原氏|12=draft}}<ref>In {{ill|Kenkū 2|ja|建久|12=draft}} (1191), {{ill|Nakahara no Hiromoto|ja|大江広元|12=draft}} was appointed as Myōhō Hakase through the recommendation of {{ill|Tsuchimikado no Michichika|ja|土御門通親|12=draft}} while serving as the {{ill|Mandokoro Betto|ja|政所別当|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Kamakura Shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|12=draft}}. This appointment was harshly criticized by {{ill|Kujō Kanezane|ja|九条兼実|12=draft}} as violating precedent, as Hiromoto was of the {{ill|Monjōdō|ja|明経道|12=draft}} branch of the Nakahara family (who later adopted the Ōe surname). However, Hiromoto resigned on November 5 of that year. It is generally believed that this resignation was due to displeasure from {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|12=draft}} over free appointments, but another view suggests that Yoritomo had plans to place the {{ill|Kebiishi|ja|検非違使庁|12=draft}} under the control of the Shogunate and appointed Hiromoto to oversee the legal aspects but made him resign after the {{ill|Kenkū 2 Uprising|ja|建久二年の強訴|12=draft}} could not be prevented (Tomohiro Saeki, ''Ichijō Yoshiyasu and Early Kamakura Public-Private Relations,'' ''Ancient Culture'' 564, 2006).</ref>.
