By the mid-{{ill|Heian period|ja|平安時代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Heian period|qq=}}, the positions became hereditary among the {{ill|Sanuki clan|ja|讃岐氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Imomune clan|ja|惟宗氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imomune clan|qq=}}, but during the medieval period, these were replaced by the renowned {{ill|Sakanoue clan|ja|坂上氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakanoue clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Nakahara clan|ja|中原氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakahara clan|qq=}}<ref>In {{ill|Kenkū 2|ja|建久|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenkū 2|qq=}} (1191), {{ill|Nakahara no Hiromoto|ja|大江広元|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakahara no Hiromoto|qq=}} was appointed as Myōhō Hakase through the recommendation of {{ill|Tsuchimikado no Michichika|ja|土御門通親|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado no Michichika|qq=}} while serving as the {{ill|Mandokoro Betto|ja|政所別当|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mandokoro Betto|qq=}} of the {{ill|Kamakura Shogunate|ja|鎌倉幕府|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura Shogunate|qq=}}. This appointment was harshly criticized by {{ill|Kujō Kanezane|ja|九条兼実|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujō Kanezane|qq=}} as violating precedent, as Hiromoto was of the {{ill|Monjōdō|ja|明経道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monjōdō|qq=}} branch of the Nakahara family (who later adopted the Ōe surname). However, Hiromoto resigned on November 5 of that year. It is generally believed that this resignation was due to displeasure from {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}} over free appointments, but another view suggests that Yoritomo had plans to place the {{ill|Kebiishi|ja|検非違使庁|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kebiishi|qq=}} under the control of the Shogunate and appointed Hiromoto to oversee the legal aspects but made him resign after the {{ill|Kenkū 2 Uprising|ja|建久二年の強訴|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenkū 2 Uprising|qq=}} could not be prevented (Tomohiro Saeki, ''Ichijō Yoshiyasu and Early Kamakura Public-Private Relations,'' ''Ancient Culture'' 564, 2006).</ref>.

