[[sn:Myōhō Hakase]] [[ja:明法博士]] [[ja:%E6%98%8E%E6%B3%95%E5%8D%9A%E5%A3%AB]] [[Category:令外官]] [[Category:大学寮]] [[Category:日本の律令制]] [[Category:Historical jurisprudence in Japan]] <!--jawiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[zh:明法博士]]

{{Infobox officeholder | name = '''Myōhō Hakase''' (明法博士) | native_name = 明法博士 | title = 明法博士 | department = [[Daigakuryō]] | type = [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] official | established = [[Shōmu]] Era, 728 CE | abolished = Medieval period | related_posts = [[Meihō-dō]] official, [[Ritsuryō]] scholar }}
'''Myōhō Hakase''' (明法博士, みょうほうはかせ) was an [[official]] belonging to the [[:en:Daigaku-ryō|Daigaku-ryō]] under the [[:en:Ritsuryō|Ritsuryō system]] in ancient Japan. It was an {{ill|Extraordinary Office|ja|令外官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Extraordinary Office|qq=}} with two positions. Initially, it was Ranked as ''Shōshichii-ge'' (正七位下). Later, it came to be filled by members of prestigious families.
== History == Myōhō Hakase was established along with {{ill|Monjō Hakase|ja|文章博士|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monjō Hakase|qq=}} under the {{ill|Kaku|ja|格式|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaku|qq=}} issued on {{ill|July 21 (lunar calendar)|ja|7月21日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/July 21 (lunar calendar)|qq=}} of [[:en:Jinki (era)|Shinki]] 5 (August 30, 728)<ref> [[:en:Shoku Nihongi|Shoku Nihongi]], entry for Daibō (8th day) of the 8th month of Taika Gannen. This record mentions dispatching Myōhō Hakase to various circuits (excluding Saikaidō) to explain the [[:en:Taihō Code|Taihō Ritsuryō]]. There are theories that Myōhō Hakase existed during the [[:en:Asuka Kiyomihara Code|Asuka Kiyomihara Ritsuryō]] period but was not established under the Taihō Ritsuryō, and that the term referred to 'officials knowledgeable in laws.' (Yukio Hisaki, ''Study of Ancient Japanese Schools'' (1990, Tamagawa University Press) ISBN 4-4720-7981-X).</ref>.
Initially, it was called '''Ritsugaku Hakase''' (律学博士), but after the establishment of {{ill|Meihōsei|ja|明法生|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meihōsei|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 明法道}} on {{ill|March 27 (lunar calendar)|ja|3月27日 (旧暦)|1=March 27 (Lunisolar)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/March 27 (lunar calendar)|qq=}} of [[:en:Tenpyō|Tenpyō]] 2 (April 18, 730), it was soon renamed '''Myōhō Hakase'''. Under Myōhō Hakase were '''Myōhō Tokugyōshō''' (明法得業生) with 2 positions and '''Myōhōshō''' (明法生) with 10 positions (later increased to 20). Over time, one of the key duties was drafting and submitting {{ill|Meihō Kanbun|ja|明法勘文|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meihō Kanbun|qq=}}, legal opinions during court discussions like {{ill|Jinden|ja|陣定|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jinden|qq=}}.
By the mid-[[:en:Heian period|Heian period]], the positions became hereditary among the {{ill|Sanuki clan|ja|讃岐氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sanuki clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Imomune clan|ja|惟宗氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imomune clan|qq=}}, but during the medieval period, these were replaced by the renowned {{ill|Sakanoue clan|ja|坂上氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakanoue clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Nakahara clan|ja|中原氏|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakahara clan|qq=}}<ref>In [[:en:Kenkyū|Kenkū 2]] (1191), [[:en:Ōe no Hiromoto|Nakahara no Hiromoto]] was appointed as Myōhō Hakase through the recommendation of {{ill|Tsuchimikado no Michichika|ja|土御門通親|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsuchimikado no Michichika|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 源通親}} while serving as the {{ill|Mandokoro Betto|ja|政所別当|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mandokoro Betto|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} of the [[:en:Kamakura shogunate|Kamakura Shogunate]]. This appointment was harshly criticized by [[:en:Fujiwara no Kanezane|Kujō Kanezane]] as violating precedent, as Hiromoto was of the {{ill|Monjōdō|ja|明経道|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Monjōdō|qq=}} branch of the Nakahara family (who later adopted the Ōe surname). However, Hiromoto resigned on November 5 of that year. It is generally believed that this resignation was due to displeasure from [[:en:Minamoto no Yoritomo|Minamoto no Yoritomo]] over free appointments, but another view suggests that Yoritomo had plans to place the {{ill|Office of Police and Justice|lt=Office of Police and Justice|lt=Kebiishi|ja|検非違使庁|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kebiishi|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 検非違使}} under the control of the Shogunate and appointed Hiromoto to oversee the legal aspects but made him resign after the {{ill|Kenkū 2 Uprising|ja|建久二年の強訴|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kenkū 2 Uprising|qq=}} could not be prevented (Tomohiro Saeki, ''Ichijō Yoshiyasu and Early Kamakura Public-Private Relations,'' ''Ancient Culture'' 564, 2006).</ref>.
